    <h2>2. Jalebi Making Machine — Price, Types & Specifications</h2>
    <p>The <strong>jalebi making machine</strong> (also called a jalebi depositor) automates the most skill-intensive part of jalebi production — the precise spiral dispensing of batter into hot oil. Traditionally, jalebi batter is squeezed through a cloth bag or dispenser by a skilled halwai who forms perfect spirals by hand. A jalebi making machine replaces this skill-dependent step with consistent, repeatable depositing.</p>

    <h3>Manual Jalebi Depositor (₹8,000 – ₹20,000)</h3>
    <p>A manual jalebi depositor is a hand-operated funnel or plunger-type device that dispenses batter in a controlled stream. The operator moves the depositor in a circular motion over the kadhai (frying pan) to form spirals. While it still requires some skill, it significantly reduces the training time needed compared to traditional cloth-bag methods.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 15–30 kg per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Batter capacity:</strong> 2–5 litres per fill</li>
      <li><strong>Material:</strong> SS 304 body with silicone nozzle</li>
      <li><strong>Spiral diameter control:</strong> Adjustable nozzle sizes (3mm to 8mm)</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> None — fully manual</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Small jalebi stalls, sweet shops with low-to-moderate jalebi demand, and operators who want improved consistency without high investment.</p>

    <h3>Automatic Jalebi Making Machine (₹50,000 – ₹2,00,000)</h3>
    <p>Automatic jalebi making machines are programmable depositing systems mounted above a frying station. The machine dispenses batter in pre-set spiral patterns directly into the oil at controlled speed and diameter. Premium models include integrated fryers with temperature control, automatic flipping mechanisms, and conveyor systems for continuous production.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 50–150 kg per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Batter hopper capacity:</strong> 10–50 litres</li>
      <li><strong>Motor power:</strong> 0.5 HP to 2 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Material:</strong> Full SS 304 construction</li>
      <li><strong>Features:</strong> Programmable spiral pattern, speed control, nozzle size adjustment, temperature display</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> Single-phase (basic) or three-phase (industrial)</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Busy sweet shops, restaurants with jalebi counters, catering operations, and mithai manufacturers producing jalebi at scale. During festival and wedding seasons, automatic jalebi machines are indispensable for meeting sudden demand surges.</p>

    <h4>Key Buying Tip for Jalebi Machines</h4>
    <p>The nozzle quality determines jalebi consistency. Cheap machines use rigid nozzles that clog frequently. Look for machines with food-grade silicone nozzles and easy-disassemble designs for cleaning. Also ensure the batter hopper has an agitator — jalebi batter tends to settle and separate, causing inconsistent dispensing if not stirred continuously.</p>

    <h2>3. Gulab Jamun Making Machine — Price, Types & Specifications</h2>
    <p>The <strong>gulab jamun making machine</strong> automates the dough ball forming and shaping process. Gulab jamun production involves preparing a khoya/mawa-based dough, forming uniform round balls, deep frying them, and soaking them in sugar syrup. The forming step is where machines deliver the most value — consistent size means consistent frying and uniform sugar absorption.</p>

    <h3>Manual Gulab Jamun Moulding Machine (₹10,000 – ₹30,000)</h3>
    <p>Manual moulding machines use spring-loaded or lever-operated ball-forming mechanisms. The operator places dough into individual cavities, presses the lever, and perfectly round balls drop out. Some models have multiple cavities (8 to 24 balls per press) for higher throughput.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 20–50 kg per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Ball weight range:</strong> 8g to 40g (interchangeable moulds)</li>
      <li><strong>Material:</strong> SS 304 or food-grade aluminium</li>
      <li><strong>Cavity count:</strong> 8, 12, 16, or 24 per press</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> None — fully manual operation</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Small to medium sweet shops where gulab jamun is one of many products but not the primary item. Also useful for catering kitchens that need to prepare batches for events.</p>

    <h3>Automatic Gulab Jamun Forming Machine (₹60,000 – ₹2,50,000)</h3>
    <p>Automatic forming machines use a hopper-fed screw extrusion system to continuously produce uniform gulab jamun balls. The operator loads dough into the hopper, and the machine extrudes, cuts, and shapes balls at high speed. Premium systems include integrated fryers and syrup soaking tanks for a complete production line.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 100–300 kg per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Motor power:</strong> 1 HP to 3 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Ball weight range:</strong> 5g to 50g (programmable)</li>
      <li><strong>Material:</strong> Full SS 304 food-contact surfaces</li>
      <li><strong>Features:</strong> Continuous feeding, adjustable ball size, speed control, auto-cutting</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> Three-phase electric</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Dedicated gulab jamun manufacturers, large mithai shops with high gulab jamun demand, and packaged sweet producers who supply to retail chains. The uniform ball size is essential for branded/packaged products where consistency defines the brand image.</p>

    <h4>Gulab Jamun Production Line Considerations</h4>
    <p>A gulab jamun making machine alone does not complete the production process. You also need:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Khoya/mawa machine:</strong> To prepare the base ingredient (see Barfi section below)</li>
      <li><strong>Deep fryer:</strong> Commercial gas or electric fryer with temperature control (₹15,000–₹60,000)</li>
      <li><strong>Sugar syrup vessel:</strong> Large SS vessel with heating element for syrup preparation</li>
      <li><strong>Soaking tanks:</strong> SS tanks for sugar syrup soaking (₹5,000–₹20,000)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Budget for the complete line, not just the forming machine. A complete gulab jamun production setup typically costs 2–3x the forming machine price alone.</p>

    <h2>4. Rasgulla Making Machine — Price, Types & Specifications</h2>
    <p>The <strong>rasgulla making machine</strong> is actually a combination of equipment rather than a single machine. Rasgulla production involves curdling milk to make chhena (paneer), draining and pressing the chhena, kneading it smooth, forming balls, and cooking them in sugar syrup. Each step can be mechanized to different degrees.</p>

