    <h3>Key Machine: Chhena Kneading + Ball Forming (₹20,000 – ₹1,50,000)</h3>
    <p>The most critical machine in rasgulla production is the chhena kneading and ball forming unit. Raw chhena must be kneaded until it reaches a perfectly smooth, elastic consistency — too little kneading causes cracks during cooking, and too much makes the rasgulla hard. Manual kneading is extremely labour-intensive and inconsistent. A kneading machine delivers the same result every time.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 40–200 kg per hour (combined kneading + forming)</li>
      <li><strong>Motor power:</strong> 1 HP to 3 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Ball weight range:</strong> 15g to 60g</li>
      <li><strong>Material:</strong> Full SS 304 (mandatory for dairy-based products)</li>
      <li><strong>Features:</strong> Variable speed kneading, adjustable ball size, auto-cutting</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Bengali sweet shops, mithai manufacturers in East India, and any sweet shop where rasgulla and related products (rosogolla, rajbhog, chamcham, sandesh) form a significant portion of revenue.</p>

    <h4>Regional Demand Note</h4>
    <p>Rasgulla making machines see the highest demand in West Bengal, Odisha, Bihar, and Jharkhand — states with strong chhena-based sweet traditions. However, with the growing popularity of rasgulla across India (especially after the GI tag dispute between West Bengal and Odisha brought national attention), demand for rasgulla machines is rising in Maharashtra, Gujarat, and South India too.</p>

    <h2>5. Barfi / Khoya Making Machine — Price, Types & Specifications</h2>
    <p>Barfi (burfi) production starts with khoya (mawa) — the base ingredient made by continuously cooking and stirring milk until it reduces to a thick, semi-solid mass. The <strong>barfi making machine</strong> category actually includes two distinct machines: the khoya/mawa machine and the barfi cutting/forming machine.</p>

    <h3>Khoya/Mawa Making Machine (₹25,000 – ₹2,00,000)</h3>
    <p>A khoya machine automates the tedious process of continuously stirring and reducing milk. Traditional khoya making requires a halwai to stand over a kadhai for 2–4 hours, stirring constantly. A khoya machine uses a rotating drum or scraper system to achieve the same result with minimal supervision.</p>

