      <li><strong>Khoya types:</strong> Can produce batti khoya, chikna khoya, and daanedaar khoya by adjusting temperature and stirring speed</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The khoya machine is perhaps the single most versatile sweet making investment. Khoya is the base for barfi, peda, kalakand, gulab jamun, milk cake, and dozens of other Indian sweets. If you only buy one machine for your mithai shop, make it a khoya machine.</p>

    <h3>Barfi Cutting & Forming Machine (₹15,000 – ₹60,000)</h3>
    <p>Once khoya is prepared and mixed with flavourings (sugar, cardamom, saffron, nuts), the barfi mixture needs to be rolled flat, cut into uniform pieces, and sometimes embossed with patterns. Barfi cutting machines use adjustable grid blades or rotary cutters to produce perfectly uniform pieces.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Manual barfi cutter:</strong> ₹15,000 – ₹25,000 (hand-operated grid cutter)</li>
      <li><strong>Semi-automatic slab roller + cutter:</strong> ₹25,000 – ₹45,000</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic barfi forming line:</strong> ₹45,000 – ₹60,000 (rolling, cutting, and conveyor)</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Any mithai shop that sells barfi, peda, or kalakand. Even small shops benefit from uniform cutting — it looks more professional in the <a href="/blog/display-counter-price-india">display counter</a> and reduces wastage from irregular pieces.</p>

