    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What is the price of a laddu making machine in India?</h3>
      <p>Laddu making machine prices in India range from ₹15,000 for a basic manual shaping machine to ₹5,00,000 for a fully automatic system with PLC controls and conveyor output. The most popular tier for commercial sweet shops is the semi-automatic range at ₹40,000–₹1,50,000, which produces 60–150 kg of laddus per hour. Prices vary based on automation level, material grade (SS 304 vs lower), brand, and production capacity. Always add 18% GST to listed prices.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Which machine is needed for motichoor laddu?</h3>
      <p>Motichoor laddu production requires two machines: a <strong>boondi dropping machine</strong> (₹15,000–₹60,000) that creates tiny boondi pearls from besan batter, and a <strong>laddu making/shaping machine</strong> (₹15,000–₹5,00,000) that forms the soaked boondi into round laddus. Some fully automatic laddu making machines (₹2,00,000+) come with integrated boondi dropping attachments. You will also need a kadhai for frying boondi and a sugar syrup vessel for soaking.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How much does a jalebi making machine cost?</h3>
      <p>A manual jalebi depositor costs ₹8,000–₹20,000, while a fully automatic jalebi making machine with integrated frying costs ₹50,000–₹2,00,000. For most commercial sweet shops, a mid-range automatic depositor in the ₹50,000–₹80,000 range offers the best balance of productivity and affordability. Key features to look for include food-grade silicone nozzles, adjustable spiral diameter, and a hopper with built-in agitator to keep the batter consistent.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What is the complete cost to set up a mithai (sweet) shop in India?</h3>
      <p>A complete mithai shop setup in India costs ₹5,00,000–₹30,00,000 depending on scale and location. This includes sweet making machines (₹2,00,000–₹15,00,000), display counters and refrigeration (₹50,000–₹5,00,000), shop interiors and furniture (₹1,00,000–₹5,00,000), licensing and FSSAI (₹10,000–₹25,000), and initial raw materials and working capital (₹50,000–₹2,00,000). For a small neighbourhood mithai shop, you can start with ₹5–8 lakh total. Read our detailed <a href="/blog/bakery-setup-cost-india">setup cost guide</a> for a complete breakdown.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Is sweet making machine investment profitable? What is the ROI?</h3>
      <p>Yes, sweet making machines are among the most profitable food equipment investments in India. A typical semi-automatic setup (₹5–8 lakh) pays for itself in 8–10 months through labour savings alone — you can reduce your workforce from 8 to 4 workers while tripling production capacity. If you leverage the increased capacity for higher sales, payback can be as quick as 2–4 months. During Diwali season alone, the production boost from automation can cover 60–80% of the total machine investment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Where can I buy sweet making machines in India?</h3>
      <p>Sweet making machines are available through multiple channels in India: (1) Direct from manufacturers like Kumar Industries, NK Industries, Girnar Food Machine, and ASVR Engineering — this gives the best prices and warranty terms. (2) Online B2B marketplaces like IndiaMART and TradeIndia where you can compare multiple suppliers. (3) Local food equipment dealers in your city — they offer convenience but typically charge 10–20% more than factory prices. (4) Through BakeDesk, where we help you connect with verified manufacturers offering competitive prices. Always visit a factory or see a live demo before purchasing machines above ₹50,000.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Do I need a separate machine for each sweet, or can one machine make multiple sweets?</h3>
      <p>Some machines are versatile across multiple products, while others are product-specific. A <strong>khoya/mawa machine</strong> is the most versatile — it produces the base ingredient for barfi, peda, kalakand, gulab jamun, and many other sweets. A <strong>ball forming machine</strong> can be used for both gulab jamun and rasgulla with interchangeable moulds. However, a <strong>jalebi depositor</strong> is jalebi-specific, and a <strong>boondi dropping machine</strong> is specific to motichoor laddu production. For maximum flexibility with a limited budget, start with a khoya machine and a ball forming machine — these cover the widest range of sweets.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What power supply do sweet making machines need?</h3>
      <p>Small manual machines need no power at all. Semi-automatic machines (0.5–2 HP motors) typically run on single-phase power supply (standard household connection in India). Fully automatic and industrial machines (3+ HP motors) require three-phase power supply, which may need a separate connection from your electricity provider — this can take 2–4 weeks and costs ₹5,000–₹15,000 depending on your state. Always check the power requirement before purchasing and budget for electrical upgrades if needed. Also consider a voltage stabilizer (₹3,000–₹10,000) to protect your machines from power fluctuations.</p>
    </div>

